ars in a defined device\u0027s topology. Note: You cannot delete the built-in zone types (EXTERNAL, INTERNAL, or DMZ). To delete a zone type In the toolbar, click your username. A drop-down menu appears. Select Administration. The Administration page appears, ...",t:"Deleting Zone Types"},"231":{i:0.00053619759023347,u:"../Content/afa-admin/Customizing-Hostgroups.htm",a:"Customizing Hostgroups You can define hostgroups to use when performing tasks such as running traffic simulation queries and/or configuring the trusted traffic you want to view.",t:"Customizing Hostgroups"},"232":{i:0.000484698166178036,u:"../Content/afa-admin/Adding-and-Editing-Host-Groups.htm",a:"To add or edit a host group In the toolbar, click your username. A drop-down menu appears. Select Administration. The Administration page appears, displaying the Options tab. Click the Compliance tab. The Compliance tab appears, displaying the Risk Profiles sub-tab. Click  . The Edit and define ...",t:"Adding and Editing Host Groups"},"233":{i:0.000484698166178036,u:"../Content/afa-admin/Deleting-Host-Groups.htm",a:"To delete a host group In the toolbar, click your username. A drop-down menu appears. Select Administration. The Administration page appears, displaying the Options tab. Click the Compliance tab. The Compliance tab appears, displaying the Risk Profiles sub-tab. Click  . The Edit and define ...",t:"Deleting Host Groups"},"234":{i:0.000974525325524849,u:"../Content/afa-admin/Customizing-Services.htm",a:"Customizing Services You can define service groups that contain one or more services to use when performing tasks such as running traffic simulation queries and/or configuring the trusted traffic you want to view.",t:"Customizing Services"},"235":{i:0.000484698166178036,u:"../Content/afa-admin/Adding-and-Editing-Service.htm",a:"Note: To define a single custom service, add a service group that contains only the desired service. To add or edit a service group In the toolbar, click your username. A drop-down menu appears. Select Administration. The Administration page appears, displaying the Options tab. Click the Compliance ...",t:"Adding and Editing Service Groups"},"236":{i:0.000484698166178036,u:"../Content/afa-admin/Deleting-Service-Groups.htm",a:"To delete a service group In the toolbar, click your username. A drop-down menu appears. Select Administration. The Administration page appears, displaying the Options tab. Click the Compliance tab. The Compliance tab appears, displaying the Risk Profiles sub-tab. Click  . The User-defined Services ...",t:"Deleting Service Groups"},"237":{i:0.00053619759023347,u:"../Content/afa-admin/Setting-Whether-Private-IP.htm",a:"By default AFA treats private IP addresses like 10.0.0.1 as non-threatening. Since these IP addresses are not routed on the public Internet, they typically represent machines that are owned by your corporation and are therefore not threatening. If desired, you can change this behavior. To set the ...",t:"Setting Whether Private IP Addresses are Trusted"},"238":{i:0.00053619759023347,u:"../Content/afa-admin/Customizing-Security-Rating.htm",a:"Note: It is possible for a device with more risks to have a higher security rating than a device with fewer risks. The Security Rating is calculated as the ratio of the number of risks detected vs. the number of risks searched for, and the total number of risks searched for differs per device. If a ...",t:"Customizing Security Rating Settings"},"239":{i:0.000854376982718707,u:"../Content/afa-admin/Customizing-the-Regulatory.htm",a:"AFA provides regulatory compliance reports for a variety of regulatory compliance standards. These reports can be accessed from the Regulatory Compliance report page of each AFA report. You can customize the Regulatory Compliance page in the following ways:  Removing and adding compliance reports. ...",t:"Customizing the Regulatory Compliance Report Page"},"240":{i:0.00171206749418262,u:"../Content/afa-admin/Removing-and-Adding-Compliance.htm",a:"To enable/disable Regulatory Compliance reports In the toolbar, click your username. A drop-down menu appears. Select Administration. The Administration page appears, displaying the Options tab. Click the Compliance tab. The Compliance page appears, displaying the Risk Profiles sub-tab.  Click the ...",t:"Removing and Adding Compliance Reports"},"241":{i:0.000666254281115319,u:"../Content/afa-admin/Customizing-the-Compliance.htm",a:"AFA reports\u0027 Regulatory Compliance page displays a compliance score which indicates the device\u0027s degree of compliance with each compliance report. AFA calculates the compliance score with the following formula: Compliance score = (X1 + WX2)/(X1 + X2 + X3) Compliance Score Formula Variables You can ...",t:"Customizing the Compliance Score Value"},"242":{i:0.000666254281115319,u:"../Content/afa-admin/Customizing-the-Compliance_1.htm",a:"AFA provides the ability to customize the compliance score severity thresholds. By default, a bad score is 55% and below (red), a moderate score is between 55% and 70% (yellow), and a good score is 70% and above (green). To customize the compliance score severity thresholds In the toolbar, click ...",t:"Customizing the Compliance Score Severity Thresholds"},"243":{i:0.0012123319867601,u:"../Content/afa-admin/Configuring-the-PCI-Zone.htm",a:"Specifying the servers in the PCI zone enables AFA to specify the vulnerability of PCI applications in the PCI regulatory compliance report. Additionally, configuring these servers enables BusinessFlow to tag which network objects intersect the PCI Zone and the applications that use these servers.  ...",t:"Configuring the PCI Zone"},"244":{i:0.00336364295910489,u:"../Content/afa-admin/Customizing-Baseline-Configuration.htm",a:"A baseline configuration compliance profile contains a set of commands to be run on the device upon analysis and the desired output for the commands, allowing you to determine the device\u0027s compliance with a certain basic configuration. In order for a device\u0027s report to include a baseline ...",t:"Customizing Baseline Configuration Compliance Profiles"},"245":{i:0.00437867137602053,u:"../Content/afa-admin/Accessing-the-Baseline-Profiles.htm",a:"To access the Baseline Profiles configuration area In the toolbar, click your username. A drop-down menu appears. Select Administration. The Administration page appears, displaying the Options tab. Click the Compliance tab. The Compliance tab appears, displaying the Risk Profiles sub-tab. Click the ...",t:"Accessing the Baseline Profiles Configuration Area"},"246":{i:0.00105652553679442,u:"../Content/afa-admin/Adding-a-New-Custom-Baseline.htm",a:"To add a new custom baseline configuration compliance profile Access the Baseline Profile configuration area. See Accessing the Baseline Profiles Configuration Area (see  Accessing the Baseline Profiles Configuration Area ). Click New.  The baseline profile form appears.  Complete the fields using ...",t:"Adding a New Custom Baseline Configuration Compliance Profile"},"247":{i:0.00105652553679442,u:"../Content/afa-admin/Duplicating-a-Baseline-Configuration.htm",a:"You can create a custom baseline configuration compliance profile by duplicating an existing baseline profile and editing the duplicate. To duplicate a baseline configuration compliance profile Access the Baseline Profile configuration area. See Accessing the Baseline Profiles Configuration Area ...",t:"Duplicating a Baseline Configuration Compliance Profile"},"248":{i:0.00105652553679442,u:"../Content/afa-admin/Editing-a-Baseline-Configuration.htm",a:"You can create a custom baseline configuration compliance profile by editing an existing baseline profile. Note: The original baseline profile will not be over-written, but it will not be available to use unless you delete the new custom baseline profile.  To edit a baseline configuration compliance ...",t:"Editing a Baseline Configuration Compliance Profile"},"249":{i:0.000484698166178036,u:"../Content/afa-admin/Deleting-a-Custom-Baseline.htm",a:"Note: You can only delete custom baseline profiles. Custom baseline profiles are indicated with a   in the Customized field. To delete a custom baseline configuration compliance profile Access the Baseline Profile configuration area. See Accessing the Baseline Profiles Configuration Area (see  ...",t:"Deleting a Custom Baseline Configuration Compliance Profile"},"250":{i:0.00183178402747663,u:"../Content/afa-admin/Example-Customizing-a-Baseline.htm",a:"The following is an example of adding an additional command and baseline requirement to an existing Cisco baseline profile.  Access the Baseline Profile configuration area. See Accessing the Baseline Profiles Configuration Area (see  Accessing the Baseline Profiles Configuration Area ). Select a ...",t:"Example: Customizing a Baseline Configuration Compliance Profile"},"251":{i:0.00319141749289485,u:"../Content/afa-admin/Customizing-Baseline-Configuration_1.htm",a:"If desired, you can create or edit custom baseline configuration compliance profiles using XML. Working in XML provides greater flexibility. Creating/Editing Baseline Configuration Compliance Profiles in XML To create/edit a baseline configuration compliance profile in XML Access the Baseline ...",t:"Customizing Baseline Configuration Compliance Profiles in XML"},"252":{i:0.00247266563460859,u:"../Content/afa-admin/Setting-AlgoSec-Firewall-Analyzer.htm",a:"Setting AlgoSec Firewall Analyzer Preferences This section explains how to configure application-wide options.   ",t:"Setting AlgoSec Firewall Analyzer Preferences"},"253":{i:0.000738542620112267,u:"../Content/afa-admin/Setting-Preferences.htm",a:"Use the following procedure to set preferences when domains are not enabled or when setting preferences in a specific domain. To set preferences In the toolbar, click your username. A drop-down menu appears. Select Administration. The Administration page appears, displaying the Options tab and the ...",t:"Setting Preferences"},"254":{i:0.000712161076047934,u:"../Content/afa-admin/General.htm",a:"General Use the General tab to set the following options. General Fields",t:"General"},"255":{i:0.000790856428611455,u:"../Content/afa-admin/Language.htm",a:"Language In the Language tab, select the language for risk titles in reports. Currently only English and Japanese are supported.",t:"Language"},"256":{i:0.000790856428611455,u:"../Content/afa-admin/Display.htm",a:"Display In the Display tab, set the display options described below. Display Fields",t:"Display"},"257":{i:0.000712161076047934,u:"../Content/afa-admin/Log-Analysis.htm",a:"Log Analysis In the Log analysis tab, set the log analysis options described below. Log Analysis Fields",t:"Log Analysis"},"258":{i:0.00126486660159891,u:"../Content/afa-admin/Proxy.htm",a:"Proxy In the Proxy tab, set the proxy options described below.  Note: If you do not know the proxy settings in your organization, contact your local network administrator. Proxy Fields",t:"Proxy"},"259":{i:0.000790856428611455,u:"../Content/afa-admin/Mail.htm",a:"Mail In the Mail tab, configure a mail server for sending automatic e-mail notifications. For information about AFA e-mail notifications, see Configuring Event-Triggered Notifications (see  Configuring Event-Triggered Notifications ).",t:"Mail"},"260":{i:0.000790856428611455,u:"../Content/afa-admin/Storage.htm",a:"Whenever AFA generates a report, the report is stored on the AFA server. Each AFA report may consume significant amounts of storage (about 75 MB* per report on average, though this can greatly vary). For example, if you have four devices whose policies are changed and analyzed daily, then AFA ...",t:"Storage"},"261":{i:0.0032310857950082,u:"../Content/afa-admin/Configuring-Report-Cleanup.htm",a:"To configure report cleanup In the toolbar, click your username. A drop-down menu appears. Select Administration. The Administration page appears, displaying the Options tab. Click Storage. The Storage tab appears. Complete the fields using the information in Storage Fields (see  Storage Fields ). ...",t:"Configuring Report Cleanup"},"262":{i:0.000712161076047934,u:"../Content/afa-admin/Workflow.htm",a:"In the Workflow tab, define the parameters for integration with an external corporate Change Management System (CMS). AFA supports integration with AlgoSec FireFlow, BMC Remedy, HP ServiceCenter (ServiceNow), or any other system supporting Web-based access. When implementing a requested change in ...",t:"Workflow"},"263":{i:0.000790856428611455,u:"../Content/afa-admin/Authentication.htm",a:"In the Authentication tab, configure the methods AFA uses for authenticating users and authenticating devices. Refer to Configuring User Authentication (see  Configuring User Authentication ) or Configuring CyberArk Integration (see  Configuring CyberArk Integration ) for more details.",t:"Authentication"},"264":{i:0.00616798373957594,u:"../Content/afa-admin/Backup-Restore.htm",a:"This section describes how to back up and restore your AlgoSec Security Management Suite from AFA using both automatic scheduling and manual processes. Backup files include ASMS users, devices, and other configurations and optional content, and can be saved locally or on a remote server. Only one ...",t:"Backup/Restore"},"265":{i:0.000484698166178036,u:"../Content/afa-admin/Backup_Restore-Details.htm",a:"Special Considerations for Distributed Architecture Environments The backup and restore functionality handles the information / settings on the appliance, only. When restoring an environment with a distributed architecture, the information will be restored to each node, but the topological ...",t:"Backup/Restore Details"},"266":{i:0.000712161076047934,u:"../Content/afa-admin/Advanced-Configuration.htm",a:"In the Advanced Configuration tab, set advanced configuration parameters, using the procedure below. Note: For information about specific configuration parameters to set, see Overriding AFA System Defaults (see  Appendix D: Overriding AFA System Defaults ). Click Add.  The Add New Configuration ...",t:"Advanced Configuration"},"267":{i:0.000484698166178036,u:"../Content/afa-admin/Managing-the-Environment.htm",a:"Managing the Environment This section describes the tasks required to maintain the AFA enviornment. For details about installing and managing licenses, see the ASMS Installation and Setup Guide.",t:"Managing the Environment"},"268":{i:0.000622029963659193,u:"../Content/afa-admin/Viewing-Information-about.htm",a:"You can view information about your AFA installation, including version and build number. To view information about your AFA installation In the toolbar, click your username. A drop-down menu appears. Select Info. The Info window appears. Click About. The About AlgoSec Firewall Analyzer window ...",t:"Viewing Information about AFA"},"269":{i:0.00196793161591999,u:"../Content/afa-admin/Managing-Issues.htm",a:"The Issues Center includes notifications for problems and potential problems in AFA. These notifications refer to AFA system issues, such as dwindling disk space, and device specific issues, such as a failed analysis. Each notification that appears in the issues center provides the details of the ...",t:"Managing Issues"},"270":{i:0.00427558618816468,u:"../Content/afa-admin/Configuring-System-Notifications.htm",a:"ASMS tracks various system metrics that trigger notifications when thresholds are exceeded. These notifications can be triggered as syslog messages, or events in the issues center.  AFA admins can modify the thresholds for each metric and the types of notifications triggered. For more details, see ...",t:"System metric notifications"},"271":{i:0.000609584398575465,u:"../Content/afa-admin/Managing-Domains.htm",a:"Managing Domains This sections describes the tasks required to manage an ASMS environment with domains enabled. This section is intended for domain management users. For more information about domains, see the AlgoSec Security Management Suite Installation and Setup Guide.  ",t:"Managing Domains"},"272":{i:0.00160997903644664,u:"../Content/afa-admin/Logging-in-to-the-Management.htm",a:"For information on logging in as a domain user, see Logging into AFA in the AlgoSec Firewall Analyzer User Guide. To log in to the management interface In your browser\u0027s Address field, type https://\u003calgosec_server\u003e/algosec/ where \u003calgosec_server\u003e is the AlgoSec server IP address or DNS name. If a ...",t:"Logging in to the Management Interface"},"273":{i:0.000688344301149473,u:"../Content/afa-admin/Adding-and-Editing-Domains.htm",a:"To add or edit a domain In the toolbar, click your username. A drop-down menu appears. Select Administration. The Administration page appears, displaying the Options tab. Click the Domains tab. The Domains tab appears, displaying a list of domains. Note: When the AFA Provider Edition license enables ...",t:"Adding and Editing Domains"},"274":{i:0.000740658109648662,u:"../Content/afa-admin/Setting-Global-Preferences.htm",a:"From the management interface, AFA users can set preferences that affect every domain and preferences that affect management interface itself. Note: To set preferences per domain, see Setting Preferences (see  Setting Preferences ). Note that some settings cannot be set globally, but only per ...",t:"Setting Global Preferences"},"275":{i:0.000688344301149473,u:"../Content/afa-admin/Deleting-Domains.htm",a:"Important: This will delete all the devices, users, and reports defined in the domain. This action cannot be undone! Note: You cannot delete the domain1 domain.  To delete a domain In the toolbar, click your username. A drop-down menu appears. Select Administration. The Administration page appears, ...",t:"Deleting Domains"},"276":{i:0.000588328034752292,u:"../Content/afa-admin/Managing-Users-and-Roles_1.htm",a:"When Domains are enabled, users and roles are split into two categories: Management users/roles and Domain users/roles. Both management users and domain users can be administrators, privileged users (AFA users), or unprivileged (FireFlow Requestors). Management users have access to the management ...",t:"Managing Users and Roles"},"277":{i:0.00102612643348663,u:"../Content/afa-admin/Adding-and-Editing-Management.htm",a:"Note: Management users can use their username and password to log in to both the management interface and to all specific domain interfaces for which they have permissions.  To add or edit a management user or role Log into the the management interface. See Logging in to the Management Interface ...",t:"Adding and Editing Management Users/Roles"},"278":{i:0.00099670982501869,u:"../Content/afa-admin/Deleting-Management-Users.htm",a:"To delete a management user or role Log into the the management interface. See Logging in to the Management Interface (see  Logging in to the Management Interface ). In the toolbar, click your username.  A drop-down menu appears. Select Administration. The Administration page appears, displaying the ...",t:"Deleting Management Users and Roles"},"279":{i:0.000484698166178036,u:"../Content/afa-admin/Integrating-AFA-with-External.htm",a:"AFA enables integration with external systems with the following features: Direct Links to the AFA Administration pages CLI tools to run batch operations SOAP and REST Web Services. See the AlgoSec Security Management Suite API Guide.  Applications to integrate with SIEM systems. See Integrating ...",t:"Integrate AFA with external systems"},"280":{i:0.000587697014288904,u:"../Content/afa-admin/Linking-Directly-to-AFA-Administration.htm",a:"Linking Directly to AFA Administration Pages AFA provides direct URLs to the AFA Administration pages. These URLs can be used to navigate to specific AFA administration pages from an external system. Direct Links to AFA Administration Pages",t:"Linking Directly to AFA Administration Pages"},"281":{i:0.00958333220199596,u:"../Content/afa-admin/Integrating-ASMS-with-Watchdog.htm",a:"ASMS can send monitoring messages using the syslog system, which is a standard for forwarding log messages in an IP network. When adding a device, you can configure ASMS to send these messages to a local system, or to an external system. External systems can read ASMS\u0027s monitoring messages and act ...",t:"Integrate ASMS with monitoring systems"},"282":{i:0.00288041979857242,u:"../Content/afa-admin/AFA-Syslog-Messages.htm",a:"AFA generates syslog messages for each analysis run, as well as additional information and administrative syslog messages as needed. In this topic: /* */ AFA analysis syslog message reference The following table provides a basic description of the syslog messages generated for AFA analysis and links ...",t:"AFA analysis syslog messages"},"283":{i:0.00380383756414291,u:"../Content/afa-admin/Understanding-Login-and-Logout.htm",a:"Each time a user logs in or out of ASMS, a log entry is created in the /var/log/messages directory. This includes internal logins, such as when FireFlow opens a session to run a traffic simulation query in AFA. When real-time monitoring is enabled, log events detailing policy changes are also logged ...",t:"AFA login and logout Syslog messages"},"284":{i:0.00380383756414291,u:"../Content/afa-admin/Policy-Change-Log-Events.htm",a:"Each time AFA detects a change via real-time monitoring, a log entry is created in the /var/log/messages directory. For more details, see  Configuring Real-Time Monitoring . AFA can also send syslog messages to a remote server. Configure the remote server in the AFA Administration area.  For more ...",t:"AFA policy change syslog messages"},"285":{i:0.000587697014288904,u:"../Content/afa-admin/Running-Batch-Operations-from.htm",a:"AFA CLI batch operations provide lower-level control over automation. This enables you to integrate AFA with other systems, for instance, an existing device backup procedure or existing change-management system.  AFA supports the following batch operations from the CLI: Running Batch Device Analyses ...",t:"Running Batch Operations from the CLI"},"286":{i:0.000651213142707941,u:"../Content/afa-admin/Running-Batch-Device-Analyses.htm",a:"The AFA multi-run utility allows you analyze several devices from the command line. With additional Unix shell scripts (not provided by AlgoSec), the AFA multi-run utility gives you the ability to integrate AFA into your automatic device backup system. The AFA multi-run utility also supports bulk ...",t:"Running Batch Device Analyses and Comparisons"},"287":{i:0.000651213142707941,u:"../Content/afa-admin/Running-Batch-Traffic-Simulation.htm",a:"AFA provides a script for running batch traffic simulation queries. The script runs each query in both directions. To run batch traffic simulation queries Create a text file containing the desired queries in the following format: source1,source2,...;destination1,destination2...;service For example: ...",t:"Running Batch Traffic Simulation Queries"},"288":{i:0.000651213142707941,u:"../Content/afa-admin/Running-Batch-IP-Address-Searches.htm",a:"AFA provides a script for executing batch IP address searches on rules. This script can be used when performing such tasks as handling shutdown or migrating a large number of servers. To run a batch IP address search Create a text file containing the desired IP addresses or ranges. The IP addresses ...",t:"Running Batch IP Address Searches"},"289":{i:0.0015917661522058,u:"../Content/afa-admin/Converting-Batch-Operation.htm",a:"AFA provides an XSLT transformation file for converting the results of batch traffic simulation queries or batch IP address operations from XML to CSV format, for easy import into Microsoft Excel or other table-based applications. Note: The output CSV file will include only those columns that exist ...",t:"Converting Batch Operation Results to CSV Format"},"290":{i:0.000484698166178036,u:"../Content/afa-admin/Troubleshooting.htm",a:"This section describes all troubleshooting